[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Investigating Java GCMSpec Issues**\n\nI'm considering the potential problems with the extractGcmSpec, especially regarding the constructor being non-null in Java 21. There's a potential issue where current reachability metadata is missing the GCMParameterSpec constructor, leading to a failure in the native direct call. I just need to remember that the instructions specify not to modify the metadata, so I'll have to work within those constraints. It's a puzzling situation that needs careful thought!\n\n**Analyzing test coverage**\n\nI'm considering how the external workflow might only run the newly generated test class for active classes. There’s something about GcmSpecUtilTest having a direct call that seems important. If there's no coverage, it could be due to the test not being included in the native image, likely tied to the class name.\n\nI think I can enhance this by using the public API of `Cipher.getParameters()` after AES/GCM encryption. I'll look into how dynamic-access reporting interacts with the caller in the library versus the tests. It's complicated but interesting!\n\n**Exploring GCMParameterSpec issues**\n\nI'm thinking that maybe the agent is filtering out `javax.crypto.spec.GCMParameterSpec` since the user-code-filter only includes `org.bouncycastle`. It's possible the dynamic access report is showing an active class from BouncyCastle. \n\nI wonder if `GCMParameterSpec` gets initialized at build-time in JDK 21. If `GcmSpecUtil.gcmSpecExtractable` returns false in native, that could lead to a NullPointerException when the constructor is called. I should check if in Native Image, `ClassUtil.loadClass` for `GCMParameterSpec` is returning null.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0fd0aa56a7d488b6016a268b15b1a48197a7ecdf0d7b0d44fa\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJosuFE8tNfkNwdWJDZPmm_3-b-ybOyOYJjH3epalmfD